<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Website on Ayham's Online Website</title><link>https://ayham.xyz/tags/website/</link><description>Recent content in Website on Ayham's Online Website</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><managingEditor>me@ayham.xyz (ayham)</managingEditor><webMaster>me@ayham.xyz (ayham)</webMaster><lastBuildDate>Wed, 23 Aug 2023 04:07:04 +0300</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://ayham.xyz/tags/website/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Pushing Static Pages to The Limit</title><link>https://ayham.xyz/posts/pushing-static-pages-to-the-limit/</link><pubDate>Sun, 04 Sep 2022 18:07:13 +0300</pubDate><author>me@ayham.xyz (ayham)</author><guid>https://ayham.xyz/posts/pushing-static-pages-to-the-limit/</guid><description>&lt;p>Static webpages are well renowned for their speed, security, and simplicity. A
very common misconception is that static webpages can&amp;rsquo;t enjoy Javascript. Here
is how I got this website to template applications that use Javascript and WASM
using Hugo&amp;rsquo;s shortcode system.&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 id="addapp-js--css-shortcode">addapp (JS + CSS) shortcode&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>Create a new shortcode file in &lt;code>theme/&amp;lt;name&amp;gt;/layouts/shortcodes/addapp.html&lt;/code>:&lt;/p>
